Wash the potatoes with cold water, taking care to scrub off dirt and other debris. Cut each potato into bite sized pieces; for small potatoes, cutting each one in half should be sufficient. Because the skin of new potatoes is so thin, there's no need to peel it. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/de/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/de/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use a paring knife to cut off any bruised or pitted parts from the potatoes. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6a/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6a/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Use tongs or a wooden spoon to toss the potatoes a bit, making sure they are covered on all sides with seasoning. Add dried herbs such as rosemary, thyme, or oregano if you'd like to flavor the potatoes. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/55/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/5/55/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-4Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Add chopped onion or garlic if you wish. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/47/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/47/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-4Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Reduce the heat to medium low and allow the potatoes to cook until tender, about 15 minutes. Check the potatoes frequently to make sure they aren't overcooking. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d6/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/d/d6/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If the potatoes absorb the butter and oil and seem to be drying out, add 1/4 cup water. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/26/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/26/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":300,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":494.83516483516485,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Toss with pieces of butter and salt and pepper to taste. Alternatively, slice the potatoes and use them to make Salad Nichoise. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1f/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-12Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-12Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1f/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-12Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-12Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Another option is to toss the potatoes with oils and spices and make a  New Potato Salad. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/73/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-12Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-12Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/7/73/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-12Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-12Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sprinkle them with salt and pepper. If you like spicier potatoes, add cayenne, chili powder, garlic powder, and any spices of your choice. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/07/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/0/07/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

For a richer dish, place a pat of butter on each potato. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bf/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/bf/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Sprinkle each potato with grated cheddar or Parmesan cheese for extra flavor. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2b/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2b/Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Cook-New-Potatoes-Step-20Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":307,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":507.3626373626374,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
